                <h1>Barney Frank, Sarah Bloom Raskin discuss 2008 economic collapse, future of financial system</h1>
                
                                    <figure class="dom-art-container my-4">
                                                    <img src="https://snworksceo.imgix.net/dtc/331103e7-da51-4ed2-996b-e54796ab4332.sized-1000x1000.jpg?w=1000" alt="" class="w-100">
                                                <div class="domphoto-caption mt-2 text-left text-md-right">
                            

                            
                        </div>
                    </figure>
                
                                    <div class="row  mt-4 mb-0 mb-md-4">
                        <div class="col-12 col-md-6">
                            <aside class="author-name">
                                    
    
                                    
            By <a href="https://www.dukechronicle.com/staff/alex-mao">Alex Mao</a>
                                    
                                <div class="mt-1">
                                    <span class="can-localize">October 26, 2017 | 12:12am EDT</span>
                                </div>
                            </aside>
                        </div>
                        <div class="col-12 col-md-6 text-left text-md-right d-print-none">
                            <ul class="social-links list-unsyled list-inline mt-4 mt-md-0">
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="http://www.facebook.com/sharer.php?u=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2017/10/barney-frank-sarah-bloom-raskin-discuss-2008-economic-collapse-future-of-financial-system" target="_blank" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="facebook" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fab fa-facebook"></i></a></li>
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="http://twitter.com/intent/tweet?url=https://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2017/10/barney-frank-sarah-bloom-raskin-discuss-2008-economic-collapse-future-of-financial-system&amp;text=Barney Frank, Sarah Bloom Raskin discuss 2008 economic collapse, future of financial system" target="_blank" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="twitter" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fab fa-twitter"></i></a></li>
                                                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="mailto:?subject=Barney%20Frank%2C%20Sarah%20Bloom%20Raskin%20discuss%202008%20economic%20collapse%2C%20future%20of%20financial%20system%20|%20The%20Chronicle&amp;message=Check%20out%20this%20article%20from%20The%20Chronicle%3A%20https%3A%2F%2Fwww.dukechronicle.com%2Farticle%2F2017%2F10%2Fbarney-frank-sarah-bloom-raskin-discuss-2008-economic-collapse-future-of-financial-system" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="email" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fa fa-envelope"></i></a></li>
                                <li class="list-inline-item"><a href="#" onclick="window.print()" class="sends-events" data-ga-category="Share" data-ga-action="click" data-ga-label="facebook" data-ga-value="CURL"><i class="fas fa-print"></i></a></li>
                            </ul>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                
                <div class="article-content w-100 mb-4">
                                            <p>Barney Frank, a former Democratic congressman from Massachusetts, and former Deputy Treasury Secretary Sarah Raskin held a discussion Wednesday about how the United States' financial services industry has evolved since the Great Recession.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Co-sponsored by the Duke University School of Law and the Kenan Institute for Ethics, the event marked an opportunity for students to gain insight from the former congressman and <a href="http://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2017/09/former-deputy-treasury-secretary-talks-rubenstein-fellows-appointment-government-experience" target="_blank">Raskin </a>who is a Rubenstein fellow.&nbsp;</p>

                        <div class="inline-ad float-none float-md-left my-4 mr-0 mr-md-4 text-center d-print-none">
                            <!-- START gryphon/ads/rectangle-inline.tpl -->
            <div id="azk18664"></div>
    <!-- END gryphon/ads/rectangle-inline.tpl -->
                        </div>

                        <p>“2008 could have been worse than the Great Depression," Frank said. "In the late 1920s, you could have one place that was doing okay and then one place that was doing poorly. When Lehman [Brothers investment bank] went under, the whole world was doing poorly.”&nbsp;</p>
<p>Frank, who gave another <a href="http://www.dukechronicle.com/article/2017/10/former-u-s-rep-barney-frank-warns-against-ideals-without-any-pragmatism-calls-for-compromise" target="_blank">talk </a>Tuesday, is one of the congressmen behind the 2010 Dodd-Frank Wall Street Reform and Consumer Protection Act, which was passed as a response to the financial crisis of 2007-2008. The act places restrictions on the way banks can invest their money, regulates financial instruments such as credit-default swaps and charters various councils that monitor the financial stability of firms that could disrupt the economy if they were to declare bankruptcy.&nbsp;</p>
<p>Following the collapse of Lehman Brothers in the fall of 2008, the government’s logic behind deciding not to bailout the bank “was made with the welfare of the average American in mind," Frank explained.&nbsp;</p>
<p>"We avoided a shutdown of the economy, [which would have caused] much more pain for the average person," he said.</p>
<p>The former congressman noted that one trend that picked up during the crisis is a distaste for government that has been exacerbated over the last few years.</p>
<p>"Government became very unpopular," he said.</p>

                        <div class="inline-ad float-none float-md-left my-4 mr-0 mr-md-4 text-center d-print-none">
                            <!-- START gryphon/ads/rectangle-article-5.tpl -->
        <div id="azk5125"></div>
<!-- END gryphon/ads/rectangle-article-5.tpl -->
                        </div>

                                                                            <p>Frank also noted that challenges remain with identifying problems in large financial institutions, saying that "how big [of an institution] is too big is an unanswerable question."</p>
<p>Raskin listed “structural changes in the economy and a consequent lack of understanding of how consumers are integrated into markets” as the primary reasons for why the financial crisis lasted so long.</p>
<p>In response to the fact that big banks are currently recording historically high profits, Raskin explained her take on the changing risk landscape of the nation.&nbsp;</p>
<p>“We are seeing in our country a gradual shift in economic risk, from firms...into the realm of the consumer," she said.</p>
                            
    
